<!--EDITING TOOLS-->

		<h2>Editing Tools</h2>
		<h4>Publication &amp; Copyright Fields<a class="int_link" name="pub_copy_fields"></a></h4>
		<dl class="guide_padding">
			<dt>Subtitle</dt>
			<dd>Provides some additional information helping to identify the Collection</dd>
			<dt>Copyright License</dt>
			<dd>This allows you to select from a set of <a href="https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/licensing-types-examples/" target="_blank">CreativeCommons licenses</a>, granting different levels of permission to use and edit your work with or without attribution. Also available is the option to assign no copyright to the Collection or note the Collection as a US Government work.</dd>
			<dt>Copyright Notes</dt>
			<dd>These can provide further details about the copyright status of the Collection (or its child Collections, Resources and Media), including contact information for an administrator or link to a further description of the source of the copyright license</dd>
			<dt>Publication Status</dt>
			<dd>Provides the option to set the newly created Collection to be publicly available. By default this is set to “Unpublished”, and is only visible to the users granted access in the <a href="#related_items">Access</a> tab. If you would like to share your work in progress, or when it is completed, it may be set to “Published”</dd>
			<dt>Author</dt>
			<dd>Provides the option to add an author to the resource (by default the author is whichever Exchange user created the item). This automatically searches all existing exchange users, any of which can be assigned as the author of the item.</dd>
			<dt>Affiliations</dt>
			<dd>The educational affiliation/interest of the Resource/Collection allows other users to identify them by their intended audience. This field is provided to allow users to filter their search results by Affiliation or browse on all Resources/Collections intended for a specific audience</dd>
		</dl>
		<h4>Formatting Tab</h4><a class="int_link" name="formatting_tab"></a></h4>
		<dl class="guide_padding">
			<dt>Media Formatting <span class="alert alert-warning">Applies only to <a href="#resource_new">Resources</a></span></dt>
			<dd>Governs how associated media are displayed for Resources ONLY. The following options are available:
				<ol>
					<li><strong>Slideshow:</strong> Displays the media in centered slideshow. A fullscreen slideshow can be opened by clicking the icon in the upper-right corner of the slideshow</li>
					<li><strong>Thumbnails:</strong> Displays a grid of the media associated with the item. The media items are displayed in a small, preview format</li>
					<li><strong>Thumbnails with Captions:</strong> Operates in the same manner as the Thumbnail option described above, but includes the user-assigned caption, whereas the basic Thumbnail option excludes this text.</li>
					<li><strong>Embed in Text:</strong> Displays no media by default, the only media displayed are the files embedded in the body text manually by the user through the <a href="resource_media">Embed Media button</a>. The embedded media is then displayed with the user-assigned settings provided through the Embed tool.</li>
				</ol>
			</dd>
			<dt>Text Placement</dt>
			<dd>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>For Resources: </strong>This provides options to place the text either <strong>Above</strong> or <strong>Below</strong> the media. (If <strong>Embed in Text</strong> is selected this has no impact on the display of the Resource</li>
					<li><strong>For Collections: </strong>This provides the options to place the text to the <strong>Left</strong> of or <strong>Above</strong> the Media.</li>
				</ul>
			</dd>
			<dt>Text Formatting <span class="alert alert-warning">Applies only to <a href="#resource_new">Resources</a></span></dt>
			<dd>This provides 2 options that enable users to customize how much text is displayed with the Resource:
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Only display the first 10 lines of text: </strong>Collapses the body text so that only the first 10 lines display with a button to "Show More". This allows users to see the body text and media on a single screen by default if the body text is lengthy. It also provides general formatting flexibility.</li>
					<li><strong>Body text collapsed by default: </strong>Sets whether the body text is collapsed or expanded by default.</li>
				</ul>
			<dt>User Interactions</dt>
			<dd>These options control the options that users have in responding and adding to the resource:
				<ol>
					<li><strong>Allow Comments:</strong> Enable users to leave free-text comments on items.</li>
					<li><strong>Allow Tags & Keywords:</strong> Enable users to add Tags (free-text terms) or Keywords (terms selected from a controlled list) on items.</li>
					<li><strong>Allow Users to Post Responses:</strong> Enable users to create an item (Resource or Collection) in "response" (see the <a href="#">Collaboration section</a> of this User Guide) with their own content to further, rebut or comment on the content of the current item.</li>
					<li><strong>Display Responses on a separate page:</strong> Sets display of user-posted Responses to either display on a section with the current item or on a separate page.</li>
				</ol>
		</dl>
		<h4>Related Items &amp; Context Tabs<a class="int_link" name="related_items"></a></h4>
		<dl class="guide_padding">
			<dt>Access</dt>
			<dd>This allows the creator of a Resource/Collection to set who can read and edit it while it its Publication Status is "Unpublished" (or to grant them the ability to edit when it is Published). These permissions can be assigned to individual users, or to groups of users. Find users or user groups by searching in the fields in this tab, which will automatically look up Exchange usernames.</dd>
			<dt>Related</dt>
			<dd>This allows users to set either other Collections and Resources as related to the current Collection. This is a more casual relationship than adding the related resource to a Collection and can be used where the materials might be similar or of note for some specific reason (which can be described in the Relationship’s caption).</dd>
			<dt>Tags &amp; Keywords</dt>
			<dd>Tags are terms that you can assign to the Collection that describe either its purpose or its contents. Once public, all users will be able to add tags to the Collection and they can be managed here.<br/><br/>Keywords perform a similar role to Tags, but are drawn from a controlled list of terms.</dd>
			<dt>Comments</dt>
			<dd>Similar to Tags you can add comments to any Collection, and once public, so can other Exchange users. From this section you can delete any comments left on your Collection by users.</dd>
			<dt>Links</dt>
			<dd>These are links to external websites, which may contain useful information or further materials pertaining to your Collection. These will appear with the link text you select displayed.</dd>
			<dt>Collections</dt>
			<dd>This identifies all Collections that this item is a member of. This is useful for quickly seeing the parents of a specific Collection and allowing you to navigate among these various Collections.</dd>
		</dl>
		
