		<h2>Searching</h2>
		<h4>Basic search<a class="int_link" name="basic_search"></a></h4>
		<p class="guide_padding">The <strong>Basic Search</strong> (available from all pages in the top navigation bar) searches across all fields of Exchange Collections and Resources. This is a useful tool to perform a general search on a topic or quickly locate a item in the Exchange.</p>
		
		<h4>Advanced search<a class="int_link" name="advanced_search"></a></h4>
		<p>The <strong>Advanced Search</strong> screen provides additional search options depending on the type of Exchange item you would like to search for:</p>
		<dl class="guide_padding">
			<dt>Collections &amp; Resources</dt>
			<dd>Can be searched specifically on title and keywords. These results can also be limited by the <strong>Affiliations</strong> associated with each item (e.g. K-12 Educator or UMMA Docent).</dd>
			<dt>UMMA Collection Objects</dt>
			<dd>In addition to title and keywords, UMMA Collection Objects can be searched on a range of fields drawn from the UMMA record for the item. These are: Style/Group/Movement, Artist/Maker, Medium and Support, Artist Nationality, Date Created, Classification/Object Type, Credit Line, Other Dates, Addtl. Classification/Object Type, Related Places, Current Location</dd>
			<dt>UMMA Exhibition</dt>
			<dd>This search allows you to find UMMA Collection Objects associated with an UMMA Exhibition. In addition to searching by title and keyword, Exhibitions can be found by: Artist/Maker, Artist Nationality, Exhibition Dates, Location.</dd>
		</dl>
		
		<h4>Query Builder<a class="int_link" name="query_builder"></a></h4>
		<p>The Query Builder provides a visual tool that users can use to create complex and detailed search queries in the Exchange. It allows users to see all of the available fields, and in many cases the available search terms.</p>

		<p>The basis of Queries are individual <strong>Rules</strong>, each of which provides a single search criteria. For example a specific artist or a keyword. If the <strong>Rule</strong> is on a field with a controlled list of terms, only these terms will be available as search criteria.</p>

		<p>These <strong>Rules</strong> can be combined into <strong>Groups</strong>  that apply them together. Within each <strong>Group</strong> the <strong>Rules</strong> are either applied through AND relationships where they ALL must match a single record for it to be returned in the search or through OR relationships where records will be returned if ANY of the <strong>Rules</strong> match an record.</p>

		<p class="guide_padding">Multiple <strong>Groups</strong> can be added to a single query to create complex searches that are either highly specific (e.g. return items by a specific artist AND which are on paper AND are from the years 1942 OR 1945. This would have the artist and material queries as separate <strong>Rules</strong> and the two year queries together in a <strong>Group</strong>.) or which have a broad reach (e.g. creating a <strong>Group</strong> to search for works by artists from a group of nations).</p>

